# {{lb|en|narrower sense}} Prejudice, discrimination, hostility or political or religious opposition directed against ethnic or religious [[Jew]]s or against [[Judaism]]; [[antijudaism]]; [[judeophobia]].
# {{lb|en|broader sense|rare|nonstandard}} Prejudice, discrimination or hostility directed against any Semitic people (ancient or modern), such as [[Samaritan]]s, [[Palestinian]]s, [[Arab]]s or [[Assyrians]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1986|author=Akhileshwar Singh|title=Political leadership of Jawaharlal Nehru|page=228|passage=But Israel's policy of '''anti-semitism''' against Palestinians was not to the liking of India.}}
#* {{quote-journal|year=2002|author=Jerusalem Center for Public Affairs|journal=Post-Holocaust and Anti-Semitism|issue=1-39|page=36|passage=At this university, a faculty member has even gone so far as to declare Zionism a form of '''anti-Semitism''' against Palestinians.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=2003|author=Jeffrey St Clair|title=The Politics of Anti-Semitism|page=41|passage=Bluntly put: if you want to end today's "anti-Semitism" against Jews, end Zionism's "'''anti-Semitism'''" against Palestinians.}}

====Usage notes====
* Though ''[[Semitic]]'' refers in a broader sense to all those who speak Semitic languages (including e.g. [[w:Arab|Arabs]] and [[w:Assyrian people|Assyrians]]), the term ''anti-Semitism'' has historically referred to prejudice against Jews alone. To avoid the confusion of the [[misnomer]], many scholars of the subject (such as [[w:Emil Fackenheim|Emil Fackenheim]]) now favor the unhyphenated ''antisemitism'' in order to emphasize that the word should be read as a single unified term, not as a meaningful root word-prefix combination.<ref>[http://www.facinghistory.org/campus/reslib.nsf/99ca830bb4f483948525717f005abfc7/2820f36c177cc758852571860065e8c2/$FILE/complete_antisemitism.pdf Antisemitism. The Power of Myth (Facing History), ''Defining Antisemitism'' page 2 (PDF page 5)]</ref><ref>“…the spelling ought to be antisemitism without the hyphen, dispelling the notion that there is an entity 'Semitism' which 'anti-Semitism' opposes.” -- Emil Fackenheim, ''Post-Holocaust Anti-Jewishness, Jewish Identity and the Centrality of Israel'', in '''World Jewry and the State of Israel'''. ed. Moshe David, p11, n2.</ref><ref>“Antisemitism is not a scientific word, and it is entitled to neither a hyphen nor a capital.” Dr. James Parkes, 1953, quoted in [http://www.nizkor.org/ftp.cgi/people/i/irving.david/jackel/postscript-kirk-6 Holocaust Almanac: David Irving's Hitler: Postscript]</ref> (See Wikipedia's article on [[w: Antisemitism#Etymology and usage|the etymology and usage]] of the term.) Use of the term to refer to prejudice against any Semitic people is rare and nonstandard.
* A very small number of writers use the term to refer to prejudice against Muslims, apparently considering them to constitute a [[Semitic]] [[race]] as opposed to only a [[religion]]. See [[Citations:anti-Semitism|citations]].

